  \begin{abstract}An SVAR model of the real exchange rate and intentional capital flows reveals that innovations to speculation can cause changes in competitiveness.  The addition of measures of speculation to existing models of exchange rates and international capital flows reduce the economic and statistical significance of conventional portfolio flows unless they are part of official intervention in the foreign exchange market.   This paper adds to the evidence that free movement international capital has disruptive effects that suggest policy intervention can be useful.  There is evidence that offical intervention in the foreign exchange market can be effective.  
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction} 
The rise in gross and net international capital flows that has taken place in the last 20 years has been well documented by \citet{PLane2007}, \citet{obstfeldtaylor}, \citet{BISFX2013} and others. The evidence has accumulated that the link between international capital flows and economic development is not as prominent in practice as it appears to be in theory.  For example, even before the Global Financial Crisis (GFC), Mishkin identified the failure of capital to flow from developed to less developed countries as conventional theory would predict; more recently, \citet{HauEquity} review the evidence on the benefits of international financial flows and find it elusive.  Indeed, international capital flows can have a very disruptive influence.  

As such, there has been increased attention on the relationships between capital flows, exchange rates and financial crisis.  \citet{CalvoSS},\citet{DornbuschSS} and \citet{KrugmanSS} have studied the effect of \emph{sudden stops} when countries suffer the financial shock of a disruption or reversal of capital inflow. The research has expanded to assess the combined influence of the \emph{sudden surge} that proceeds the outflow and to a consideration of the range of gross inflows and outflows that affect the balance of payments.  For example, \citet{cavalloSS} provide an analysis and taxonomy of stops based on the composition of the financial account adustment and the effect that it has on growth, the exchange rate and inflation.  
      
This increased skepticism over the benefits of the free-flow of capital has renewed interest in capital controls and other means of reducing their influence.  This is helped by tentative evidence from Malaysia, China and Brazil that they can be effective in practice.  \citet{brunnermeier2014international} develop a two-country neoclassical stochastic growth model where banking credit can be excessive and can reverse.  Capital controls or macroprudential measures can improve model outcomes. \citet{KatanoCapital} compares the effect of capital controls and perfect capital mobility and finds that the less efficient the financial system the more likely that capital controls will be welfare enhancing. \citet{Korinek2011} makes the case for capital flows on the basis that individual investors do not internalise the increase in the size of the aggregate financial shock that individual inflows cause.  He calls for liquidity-adjusted taxes to price this externality.   

LIquidity-adjusted measures reflect the fact that evidence suggests that the more short-term and speculative the capital flow, the more disruptive and less beneficial:  foreign direct investment can have a positive influence and is slow to reverse; portfolio flows are less helpful and can be swiftly withdrawn; there is much less evidence on speculation. Need a reference for sudden stops and the composition of capital flows. \citet{Gregoriocapcont} assesses Chinese capita controls and finds that though they do not have a major effectve on the level of the exchange rate, they encourge capital inflows of a longer maturity.   
% there needs to be some evidence for this. 

Razin, Sadka and Yuen (1998) [real cite needed and the Gregorio cap con above also has to be found] identify a pecking order to financial flows with FDI having the least cost in terms of reversal risk; equity flows generally being less prone to stops and reversals; and, debt, particularly with short maturity, being the most risky. Roderick and Velasco study xx countries and find that those with the highest oroportion of debt are teh most likely to suffer financial flow reversal. 
There appear to be two major components to speculative currency activity: the a momentum effect and the carry-trade. Each of these can contribute to the osscilation of capital surges and capital stops.  The momentum is associated wtih a graduate evolution in sentiment from positive to negative.  The carry trade is tries to take advantage of the failure of Uncovered-interest-parity (UIP) to hold.  It usually involves borrowing at releatively low rates in \emph{funding currencies} such as the US dollar, Japanese yen, Swiss franc or Euro and using the proceeds to deposit in higher interest rates currencies.  This can cause disruption when large inflows become a constraint on monetary policy and even larger problems when inflows reverse. 

However, identifying speculative flows has been a challenge due to the scarcity of data.  A standard approach has been to use data for overseas bank lending by the Bank for International Settlements (BIS). For example, \citet{Bruno2014} model the global liquidity cycle of internationa banks; \citet{AdamsKaneGlobal} tries to assess the relative importance of willingness to lend, liqudity and solvency in determing capital flow; \citet{Cerutti2014} combine BIS with local bank data to assess links between international banks. However, it is difficult within this data to distinguish between bank lending for real business projects and that for speculative activity.  A bank loan that originates from overseas is much more likely to be beneficial for the recipient country than one that is merely financing an exchange rate speculation.  

A new practical interest in the relationship between the real exchange rate and capital flows developed at start of the millenium amidst the struggle to understand the initial weakenss of the euro against the US dollar and the related disconnect between the rise in the US current account deficit and the steady standing of the US dollar.  For example the May 2001 World Economic Outlook from the IMF highlighted the failure of the models of the current account or interest rate differentials to account for US dollar strength \citet{imfweo2001} and the December 20000 issue of the Bank of England's Financial Stability Review considered the effect of portfolio flows.  The latter highlighting the \$206.1bn turnaround in US erquity and foreign direct investment flows from an outflow of \$76.0bn in 1995-96 to an inflow of \$130.1bn in 1999-2000 as well as the mirror increase in the current account deficit \citet{BOEFSR2000}.
 
However, there has been only limited progress in the development of exchange rate models that depend on capital flows.  There have been three major problems in their contruction:  deciding on the variables that will be used, dealing with the issue of endogeneity and modelling the relationship between portfolio choice and the exchange rate.  There are three important contributions:  creating a structural model of international capita flows and the real exchange rate; adding speculation to the capital flows that are assessed; assessing the effect of speuclation in the model.   

\section{The model}\label{secref:2}
\subsection{Equilibrium}
Purchasing power parity (PPP) remains the standard  method to understand the long-run evolution of exchange rates.  \citet{Cassel1916Present} is credited with first identifying the relationship between relative prices and the exchange rate.  However, there is intense debate about how far PPP holds and the \emph{Penn Effect}, whereby the real exchange rate appears to appreciate with economic development, is one of the factors suggesting that this relationship is not stable. There is evidence that exchange rates can show persistent divergence from the `equilibrium' of PPP, so that the \emph{real exchange rate} that is adjusted for prices is not stable and may not even be \emph{stationary}. \citet{TaylorPPP} discusses the power of unit root tests that have been applied to the real exchange rate and the issue of stationarity.  Deviations from PPP are also called gains and losses in international competitiveness and have been associated with adverse effects on economic activity from Keynes' Economic Consequences of Mr. Churchill \citep{Keynes1925Churchill} through to current debate about competitiveness in the euro area. 

Some of the explanations for the deviations from PPP equilibrium revolve around the way that productivity in the traded-goods sector differs from that for non-traded. See \citet{harrod1933international}, \citet{balassa1964ppp} and \citet{samuelson1964trade} amongst others for an overview of this. Alternatively, this over-valuation may also be a consequence natural resource or other endowements that improve the balance of payments and drive up the value of the exchange rate relative to the PPP valuation.  While the \emph{Dutch disease} refers to the effect of a natural endowment can have on the real exchange rate and competitiveness, there has also been more recent attention on the way that a developed financial sector has affected the traded goods sector of countries like the US and the UK.  See \citet{CordenNeary} for a formal overview of the Dutch disease and \citet{SachsDutch} for an application of this to the UK. Here the infow of capital is regarded as a key factor behind the loss of competitiveness.    More recently, there has also been attention on the way that capital flows can affet the real exchange rate.  
