\subsection{Capital Flow}\label{secref:3}
Standard models of exchange rates have put the emphasis on the goods market. \citet{OandR} provide an overview of the most widely used open-economy macro model that concentrates on relative prices and the adjustment via the current account.  International financial flows can be incorporated so that there are adustments to country-specific exogenous innovations like productivity shocks through inter-temporal adjustments.  This involves capital flows and changes in the stock of net international investments. See \citet{obstfeld2000new}, \citet{OandRedux} and \citet{lane2001new} for a survey of the literature. 

The financial account and the role that portfolio adjustment plays in the evolution of exchange rates has generally received less attention.  One of the founding models of international capital flows was presented by \citet{Branson1971}. This is a stock, equilibrium, reduced-form model where changes in capital flows depend on changes in relative interest rates and changes in the the size of the overall stock of savings.  This model takes the form

\begin{equation}
\Delta B^f = a_0 + a_1 \Delta R + a_2 \Delta R^* + a_3 \Delta E + u
\end{equation}

where $B^f$ is the share of foreign assets in the portfolio, $R$ is the domestic interest rate, $R^*$ is the overseas interest rate and $E$ is the level of risk aversion.  In this fixed-exchange-rate era, the risk on foreign assets is primarily an excahange rate realignment risk that is acccomodated, in this case, by a shift in the empirical analysis through the use of dummy variables. 

The model is criticised by  \citet{Kouri1974International} and others for provding biased estimates of the elasticity of capital flows to interest rates, due to the failure to deal with the issue of endogeneity and for abstracting from the effect of the domestic bond supply on capital outflows. \citet{Kouri1974International} develop a Portfolio Equilibrium model and extend Branson by adding the traditional monetary approach to the balance of payments. Capital flows are therefore affected by the domestic excess demand for money and interest rates are endogenous.   The model is very effective in explaining the capital flows in Germany, Italy, the Netherlands and Australia in the perild fixed exchange rate period of 1964 to 1970. It is estimated as,   

\begin{equation}
TC = \Delta Y + \Delta R^* + \Delta NDA + \Delta RR, 
\end{equation}

where $TC$ are the total private capital flows, $Y$ is national income, $\delta R^*$ is the change in the overseas interest rate, $NDA$ are the net domestic assets of the central bank and $RR$ are the reserve requirements. In thoery the equation will also include domestic and overseas wealth and overseas income.  However, in the original, these elements have been dropped due to a lack of data. The exchange rate is represented by a series of dummy variables to cover expected changes in the value of the exchange rate peg.   
  
The increased availability of data has encouraged an interest in capital flows and the exchange rate.  Key international organisations have sought to improve the information that is being provided about international capital flows. This includes the IMF's \citet{website:imfportfolio}, \citet{website:worldbankdebt} and \citet{website:bisdata} international banking data. There have also been a number of private initatives that have amalgamated existing information to create data series that can be used to analyse the key components of international capital.  Amongst these are \citet{PLane2007} as well as \citet{BoEdata}. More detailed and complete data has allowed more attention to be devoted to capital flows and their effects as well as details like the relationship between gross and net flows (example) and valuation effects from \citet{gourinchas2007world}. This has allowed new models to be tested against  the empirical evidence.   

The model used in this paper is an extension to the one used in \citet{HauEquity}.  That model concentrates on the financial account of the balance of payments and uses the microstructure idea of order-flow to account for changes in the exchange rate.  However, while in the microstructure literature \citet{Evans2002Order}, \citet{Lyons1995Microstructure} and \citet{rime2010exchange} explain movements in currency with knowledge about market-maker and dealer orders, here the movement of international capital is the fulcrum of adjustment.

On the assumption that all dividends are repatriated, Hau and Rey express the capital outflow for the equity market $(Q_t)$ as

\begin{equation}
dQ_t = E_tK_t^{h*}D_t^hdt - K_t^fD_t^fdt + dK_t^fP_t^f - E_tdK_t^{h*}P_t^h
\end{equation}

where $E_t$ is the exchange rate at time $t$ expressed as foreign units of domestic currency; equity holding at time $t$ are $K_t$, divided between home equities $K_t^h$ and foreign $K_t^f$. 
